Data Preprocessing¶

From the above box-plots, a few outliers can be detected, which affects the model performance. By comparing model performance before and after removing these outliers, a slight improvement in model accuracy was observed when removing the following points.

In [ ]:
# Changing datatype for class column to string
wine['class'] = wine['class'].astype('string')

# Creating new dataframes to store class and features for wine database
wine_class = wine['class']
wine_features = wine[ wine.columns[1:] ]

# Creating training and testing sets
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    wine_features, wine_class,
    test_size=0.25, random_state=30, shuffle=True
)

print('\nSize of Training and Testing Sets:\n')
print('Training Set    ', str( len(x_train) ))
print('Testing Set     ', str( len(x_test) ))

from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Training Decison Tree Classifier Model on training set
clf_dt = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier().fit( x_train, y_train )

# Visualizing the Decision Tree Classifier Model
plt.figure( figsize=(20,15) )
tree.plot_tree( clf_dt, feature_names=wine.columns[1:], class_names='123', filled=True )
plt.show()

# Calculating Model Accuracy for Decision Tree on testing set
print("The accuracy of Decision Tree Model is:")
acc_dt = clf_dt.score( x_test, y_test ) * 100
print( acc_dt )

Random Forest vs Decision Trees Comparision¶

Accruracy from Decision Tree Models are:

  • Decision Tree w/holdoffs 92.68 %
  • Decision Tree w/CV 87.61 %

Whereas, accuracy obtained from Random Forest Models are:

  • Random Forest w/holdoffs 97.56 %
  • Random Forest w/CV 96.87 %
  • Extremely Randomized Tree w/CV 97.53 %

There appears to be a sharp increase in accuracy (9%) when using Random Forest, instead of a single tree. Additionally, randomizing the trees gives further 0.7% increase in accuracy.

K-Nearest Neighbors¶

KNN Preprocessing¶

Since, K-Nearest Neighbors is very succeptible to noise due to excessive features, only best features are selected for classification. Moreover, KNN requires the data to be in the standardized form, to negate the effects of high-magnitude values in any chosen variable.

From the pair-plots in the Data Exploration section above, (alcohol, tot_phenols, flavanoids) provided the best distinction among wine classes, while (malic_acid, non_flavanoid_phenols, hue, diluted_wines_0D280_0D315, proline) provided adequate distinction with some overlap.

Resources

  • https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/preprocessing.html#:~:text=6.3.3.%20Normalization%C2%B6
  • https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.preprocessing.normalize.html#sklearn.preprocessing.normalize
In [ ]:
# Creating new dataframes to store best features for wine database
wine_best_features = wine[ wine.columns[[1, 6, 7, 2, 8, 11, 12, 13]] ]
In [ ]:
# Vectorization
x_vec = wine_best_features.to_numpy()
y_vec = wine_class.to_numpy()

# Normalizing all features in the wine dataset
from sklearn.preprocessing import normalize
x_vec = normalize( x_vec )

KNN for k (0 to 50) with 10-Fold Cross-Validation¶

In [ ]:
# Calculating mean accuracy from 10-Fold Cross Validation for each value of k between 1 and 50.
cv_score_50_knn = pd.DataFrame( columns=['k','Accuracy'] )
for k in range(1, 51):
    clf_50_knn = neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier( n_neighbors=k )
    cv_score = cross_val_score(clf_50_knn, x_vec, y_vec, cv=10).mean() * 100
    cv_score_50_knn.loc[ len(cv_score_50_knn) ] = [ k, cv_score ]

# Calculating Model Accuracies obtained from Cross Validation
print("The mean accuracy from 10-Fold Cross Validation for each value of k between 1 and 50 are:")
print( cv_score_50_knn )

print("\nThe mean accuracy % from 10-Fold Cross Validation for best k:")
acc_knn_best_k_10_cv = cv_score_50_knn[ cv_score_50_knn.Accuracy==cv_score_50_knn.Accuracy.max() ]
print( acc_knn_best_k_10_cv )
acc_knn_best_k_10_cv = cv_score_50_knn.Accuracy.max()

K-Nearest Neighbor vs Random Forest vs Decision Trees Comparision¶

[NOTE: KNN is highly succeptible to noise, as higher number of features in the model translates to higher chances of overfitting the model on random noise. Hence, only selected features were used to improve the model accuracy. In contrary, rest of the algorithms include some form of feature selection, thereby not requiring manual intervention for feature selection.]

Accuracy obtained from Random Forest Models are:

  • Random Forest w/holdoffs 97.56 %
  • Random Forest w/CV 96.87 %
  • Extremely Randomized Tree w/CV 97.53 %

Whereas, accuracy obtained from K-Nearest Models are:

  • K-nearest w/CV 90.04 % @ k=10
  • K-Nearest k from 0 to 50 w/CV 91.29 % @ k=8 (best k)

Accuracy for K-nearest Model with k=10 is 7% lower than the Random Forest Model, and 7.5% lower than the Extremely Randomized Tree Model. Upon training multiple models with different values of k, the best accuracy obtained was 91% at k=8 (best k), which is 1.25% higher than k=10 model. The plausible cause for low model performance is the high dimensionality, which is one of the biggest drawbacks of KNN. The accuracy of the model can be further improved by iterating the model training over various pairs of features.

GaussianNB vs MultiNomialNB model comparision:¶

Mean Accuracy from Multinomial Naive Bayes Classificaiton Model with 10-Fold Cross Validation is:

  • MultinomialNB w/CV 85.18 %

Whereas, Mean Accuracy obtained from Gaussian Naive Bayes Classificaiton Model with 10-Fold Cross Validation is:

  • GaussianNB w/CV 97.50 %

There is a huge increase in model classification accuracy (12%) when using Gaussian model instead of Mulinomial. The cause for such a steep difference could be that, Multinomial Naive Bayes Algorithm is more suitable for variables that indicate frequency of occurences or counts, as opposed to Gaussian Naive Bayes algorithm which is suitable for all continuous Ratio-numeric data.

Source: https://www.i2tutorials.com/what-is-the-difference-between-gaussian-multinomial-and-bernoulli-naive-bayes-classifiers/

Support Vector Machines¶

SVM Model by Radial Basis Function (RBF) with 10-Fold Cross-Validation¶

from sklearn.svm import SVC

# Performing 10-Fold Cross Validation on SVM Model by rbf (radial basis function)
clf_svc = SVC()
cv_score_svc = cross_val_score( clf_svc, wine_features, wine_class, cv=10 )

# Calculating Model Accuracies obtained from Cross Validation
print("The Accuracy obtained from performing 10-Fold Cross Validation are: \n")
print( list(cv_score_svc * 100) )

print("\nThe mean accuracy % from 10-Fold Cross Validation is:")
acc_svc_rbf_10_cv = cv_score_svc.mean() * 100
print( acc_svc_rbf_10_cv )

print("\nThe maximum accuracy % from 10-Fold Cross Validation is:")
print( cv_score_svc.max() * 100 )

SVM Model by testing various kernels with 10-Fold Cross-Validation¶

Resources

  • https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.svm.SVC.html#sklearn.svm.SVC
In [ ]:
# Calculating mean accuracy from 10-Fold Cross Validation for linear, sigmoid and poly kernels
svm_kernels = ['linear', 'sigmoid', 'poly']
cv_score_k_svm = pd.DataFrame( columns=['kernel','Accuracy'] )

for k in svm_kernels:
    clf_k_svm = SVC( kernel=k )
    cv_score = cross_val_score( clf_k_svm, wine_features, wine_class, cv=10 ).mean() * 100
    cv_score_k_svm.loc[ len(cv_score_k_svm) ] = [ k, cv_score ]

# Calculating Model Accuracies obtained from Cross Validation
print("The mean Accuracy obtained by all kernels from performing 10-Fold Cross Validation are: \n")
print( cv_score_k_svm )

print("\nThe maximum accuracy % from all kernels with 10-Fold Cross Validation is:")
print( cv_score_k_svm[ cv_score_k_svm.Accuracy==cv_score_k_svm.Accuracy.max() ])
acc_svc_lin_10_cv = cv_score_k_svm.Accuracy[0]
acc_svc_sig_10_cv = cv_score_k_svm.Accuracy[1]
acc_svc_pol_10_cv = cv_score_k_svm.Accuracy[2]

The mean Accuracy obtained by all kernels from performing 10-Fold Cross Validation are: 

    kernel   Accuracy
0   linear  95.073529
1  sigmoid  16.176471
2     poly  71.470588

The maximum accuracy % from all kernels with 10-Fold Cross Validation is:
   kernel   Accuracy
0  linear  95.073529
